## Credit Impairment

Refer to the Audit Committee Report (page 117); Accounting polic/i.rightes (page 328); Note 8 of the financ/i.rightal statements; and relevant credit risk disclosures (includ/i.rightng pages 203 and 234) At 31 December 2021, the Group reported total credit impa/i.rightrment balance sheet provis/i.righton of $6,209 mill/i.righton (2020: $7,145 mill/i.righton).

Management's judgements and estimates are especially subject/i.rightve due to sign/i.rightficant uncertainty associated with the assumptions used. Assumptions with increased complexity in respect of the tim/i.rightng and measurement of expected credit losses (ECL) include:

- · Staging - Allocation of assets to stage 1, 2, or 3 on a timely basis using criter/i.righta in accordance with IFRS 9;
- · Model output and adjustments - Accounting interpretat/i.rightons, modelling assumptions and data used to build and run the models that calculate the ECL, includ/i.rightng the appropriateness, completeness and valuation of post-model adjustments applied to model output to address risks not fully captured by the models;
- · Economic scenarios - Sign/i.rightficant judgements involved with the determinat/i.righton of parameters used in Monte Carlo Simulat/i.righton and the evaluation of the appropriateness of using Monte Carlo Simulat/i.righton with regards to whether the simulat/i.righton can suffic/i.rightently capture the non-linear/i.rightty of ECL and appropriately generate a wide enough range of possible outcomes;
- · Management overlays - Appropriateness, completeness and valuation of risk event overlays to capture risks not ident/i.rightfied by the credit impa/i.rightrment models, includ/i.rightng the considerat/i.righton of the risk of management override; and
- · Indiv/i.rightdually assessed ECL allowances - Measurement of ind/i.rightvidual provis/i.rightons includ/i.rightng the assessment of probabil/i.rightty weighted recovery scenarios, exit strategies, collateral valuations and time to collect.

The above complexit/i.rightes are further exacerbated by the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic, particularly due to its dynamic nature and the divers/i.rightty of its impact across geographies and time. The most notable risk in this respect remains the appropriateness of the management COVID-19 overlay recognised with/i.rightn the ECL. The level of risk remains consistent with the prior year.

We evaluated the design and operating effectiveness of controls relevant to the Group's processes over material ECL balances, includ/i.rightng the judgements and estimates noted, involv/i.rightng EY special/i.rightsts to assist us in performing our procedures to the extent it was appropriate. These included:

- · credit monitor/i.rightng;
- · controls over the allocation of assets into stages such as management's monitor/i.rightng of stage effectiveness;
- · completeness and accuracy of data;
- · review and approval of multiple economic scenarios;
- · model governance, includ/i.rightng model monitor/i.rightng, model validat/i.righton and review and approval of post model adjustments;
- · review and approval of management overlays; and
- · review and approval of the ind/i.rightvidually assessed ECL.

In evaluating the controls, we obtained the relevant papers and minutes of the executive forums that discuss and approve the credit models and ECL allowances for evidence of executive review and challenge.

We performed an overall stand-back assessment of the ECL

allowance levels by stage to determine if they were reasonable by consider/i.rightng the overall credit quality of the Group's portfolios, risk profile, impact of COVID-19 includ/i.rightng geographic considerat/i.rightons and vulnerable sectors. We also assessed the effect of government support measures in key locations (e.g., payment deferrals), which may delay or mask stage migrat/i.rightons. Our assessment also included the evaluation of the macroeconomic environment by consider/i.rightng trends in the economies and industr/i.rightes to which the Group is exposed. We performed peer benchmarking where available to assess overall staging and provis/i.righton coverage levels.

Staging - We evaluated the criter/i.righta used to allocate financ/i.rightal assets to stage 1, 2 or 3 in accordance with IFRS 9. We reperformed the staging distr/i.rightbution for a sample of financ/i.rightal assets and assessed the reasonableness of staging downgrades applied by management.

To test credit monitor/i.rightng which largely drives the probabil/i.rightty of default estimates used in the staging calculation, we challenged the risk ratings for a sample of performing accounts and other accounts exhib/i.rightting risk characterist/i.rightcs such as financ/i.rightal diff/i.rightculties, deferment of payment, late payment and watchlist. We also considered the vulnerable sectors (as defined on page 229 in the annual report) impacted by COVID-19.

## 8. Credit impa/i.rightrment continued

Sign/i.rightficant increase in credit risk (Stage 2) If a financ/i.rightal asset experiences a sign/i.rightficant increase in credit risk (SICR) since in/i.righttial recognit/i.righton, an expected credit loss provis/i.righton is recognised for default events that may occur over the lifet/i.rightme of the asset.

Sign/i.rightficant increase in credit risk is assessed by comparing the risk of default of an exposure at the reporting date to the risk of default at orig/i.rightnation (after taking into account the passage of time). Sign/i.rightficant does not mean statist/i.rightcally sign/i.rightficant nor is it assessed in the context of changes in expected credit loss. Whether a change in the risk of default is sign/i.rightficant or not is assessed using a number of quantitat/i.rightve and qualitat/i.rightve factors, the weight of which depends on the type of product and counterparty. Financ/i.rightal assets that are 30 or more days past due and not credit-impa/i.rightred will always be considered to have experienced a sign/i.rightficant increase in credit risk. For less material portfolios where a loss rate or roll rate approach is applied to compute expected credit loss, sign/i.rightficant increase in credit risk is primar/i.rightly based on 30 days past due.

Quantitat/i.rightve factors include an assessment of whether there has been sign/i.rightficant increase in the forward-looking probabil/i.rightty of default (PD) since orig/i.rightnation. A forward-looking PD is one that is adjusted for future economic condit/i.rightons to the extent these are correlated to changes in credit risk. We compare the residual lifet/i.rightme PD at the balance sheet date to the residual lifet/i.rightme PD that was expected at the time of orig/i.rightnation for the same point in the term structure and determine whether both the absolute and relative change between the two exceeds predetermined thresholds. To the extent that the differences between the measures of default outlined exceed the defined thresholds, the instrument is considered to have experienced a sign/i.rightficant increase in credit risk.

Qualitat/i.rightve factors assessed include those linked to current credit risk management processes, such as lending placed on non-purely precautionary early alert (and subject to closer monitor/i.rightng).

A non-purely precautionary early alert account is one which exhib/i.rightts risk or potential weaknesses of a material nature requir/i.rightng closer monitor/i.rightng, supervis/i.righton, or attention by management. Weaknesses in such a borrower's account, if left uncorrected, could result in deteriorat/i.righton of repayment prospects and the likel/i.righthood of being downgraded. Indicators could include a rapid erosion of posit/i.righton with/i.rightn the industry, concerns over management's abil/i.rightty to manage operations, weak/ deteriorat/i.rightng operating results, liqu/i.rightdity strain and overdue balances among other factors.

Credit-impa/i.rightred (or defaulted) exposures (Stage 3) Financ/i.rightal assets that are credit-impa/i.rightred (or in default) represent those that are at least 90 days past due in respect of princ/i.rightpal and/or interest. Financ/i.rightal assets are also considered to be credit-impa/i.rightred where the obligors are unlikely to pay on the occurrence of one or more observable events that have a detrimental impact on the estimated future cash flows of the financ/i.rightal asset. It may not be possible to ident/i.rightfy a single discrete event but instead the combined effect of several events may cause financ/i.rightal assets to become credit-impa/i.rightred.

- · Evidence that a financ/i.rightal asset is credit-impa/i.rightred includes observable data about the following events:
- · Sign/i.rightficant financ/i.rightal diff/i.rightculty of the issuer or borrower;
- · Breach of contract such as default or a past due event;
- · For economic or contractual reasons relating to the borrower's financ/i.rightal diff/i.rightculty, the lenders of the borrower have granted the borrower concession/s that lenders would not otherwise consider. This would include forbearance actions (page 331);
- · Pending or actual bankruptcy or other financ/i.rightal reorganisat/i.righton to avoid or delay discharge of the borrower's obligat/i.righton/s;
- · The disappearance of an active market for the applicable financ/i.rightal asset due to financ/i.rightal diff/i.rightculties of the borrower;
- · Purchase or orig/i.rightnation of a financ/i.rightal asset at a deep discount that reflects incurred credit losses

Lending commitments to a credit-impa/i.rightred obligor that have not yet been drawn down are included to the extent that the commitment cannot be withdrawn. Loss provis/i.rightons against credit-impa/i.rightred financ/i.rightal assets are determined based on an assessment of the recoverable cash flows under a range of scenarios, includ/i.rightng the realisat/i.righton of any collateral held where appropriate. The loss provis/i.rightons held represent the difference between the present value of the expected cash shortfalls, discounted at the instrument's orig/i.rightnal effective interest rate, and the gross carrying value (includ/i.rightng contractual interest due but not paid) of the instrument prior to any credit impa/i.rightrment. The Group's defin/i.righttion of default is aligned with the regulatory defin/i.righttion of default as set out in the UK's onshored capital requirements regulations (Art 178).
